{"version":"0.3.1","markups":[],"atoms":[],"cards":[["card-markdown",{"cardName":"card-markdown","markdown":"Now that you have your environment set up, let's now learn how to establish a connection.

ProximaX supports two types of connection, the local and remote peer connection, but for this guide we will only be using the ```RemotePeerConnection```

### Establishing A Remote Peer Connection
```RemotePeerConnection``` are for clients who want to use a remote storage and doesn't want or prefer to use its own device to participate on the storage network.

To establish a ```RemotePeerConnection```, create a java class in your project and write the following code: 

```java
import io.proximax.xpx.facade.connection.RemotePeerConnection;
import io.proximax.xpx.factory.ConnectionFactory;

public class establishConnection {
    public static RemotePeerConnection remotePeerConnection = new RemotePeerConnection("https://testnet.gateway.proximax.io");
}
```

Aside from the testnet connection above, one can also use the following testnet gateways.

- https://testnet1.gateway.proximax.io
- https://testnet2.gateway.proximax.io
- https://testnet3.gateway.proximax.io

#### What's Next?
Let's start [coding your first ProximaX Application](http://blog.proximax.io/coding-your-first-application/)"}]],"sections":[[10,0]]}

{"version":"0.3.1","markups":[],"atoms":[],"cards":[["card-markdown",{"cardName":"card-markdown","markdown":"From the previous tutorial you learned how to [establish a connection](http://blog.proximax.io/establishing-a-connection/). Now we will start coding your first ProximaX application's functionalities.

For this tutorial, we will be building a simple Java swing application in IntelliJ IDEA using Maven. It will have the ProximaX SDK's core features: Upload, Download and Search.

To get started let's create the interface using IntelliJ's GUI Form builder. Create something like this:
![sc_sampleApp-2](/content/images/2018/08/sc_sampleApp-2.jpg)

### Let's get into coding!
</br>
For the BROWSE button, it should allow you to open the file chooser to browse and select the file that you want to upload, then display the path in a text field. To do that, add in the following code to your main class.

```java
btnselect.addActionListener(new ActionListener()
        {
            public void actionPerformed(ActionEvent e)
            {
                JFileChooser fileChooser = new JFileChooser();
                fileChooser.setFileSelectionMode(JFileChooser.FILES_ONLY);
                fileChooser.setAcceptAllFileFilterUsed(false);
                int val = fileChooser.showOpenDialog(null);
                if (val == JFileChooser.APPROVE_OPTION) {
                txtFilePath.setText(fileChooser.getSelectedFile().toString());
                }
            }
        });
```

Now that we already have the path of the file we're going to upload, let's code for the UPLOAD button. To do an Upload, we need to have an upload parameter. Since we will be uploading a file, we will be using the ```UploadFileParameter```

An ```UploadFileParameter``` has the following attributes:

| Fields       | Description       |
| ------------- |---------------|
| senderPrivateKey       | The Private Key of the account initiating the upload       |
| receiverPublicKey       | The Public Key of the account receiving the upload      |
| file       | The file you are uploading      |
| keywords       | A custom field that can be used to tag a specific file. This has a limit of 80 characters      |
| metadata       | A json structured text that can be used to add additional text or structure data. This has a limit of 400 characters.       |

For this tutorial, we're going to use the 'Tags' text field for the *keywords* and 'Uploader', and the current date for the *metadata*.
Specifying your *keywords* and *metadata* can help you with grouping your files and do more filtered searching.

Our parameter is complete, and we can now do the upload. For your UPLOAD button, add the following code:

```java
//initialize the variables
private static File filePath;
private static String KEYWORDS= "";
private static Map<String, String> METADATA = new HashMap<>();


btnUpload.addActionListener(new ActionListener()
        {
            public void actionPerformed(ActionEvent e)
            {
                filePath = new File(txtFilePath.getText());
                METADATA.put("Uploader", txtUploader.getText());
                METADATA.put("Date Uploaded", LocalDate.now().toString());
                KEYWORDS = txtTags.getText();

                try {

                    Upload upload = new Upload(remotePeerConnection);

                    UploadFileParameter parameter = UploadFileParameter.create()
                            .senderPrivateKey(yourTestPrivateKey)
                            .receiverPublicKey(yourTestPublicKey)
                            .file(filePath)
                            .keywords(KEYWORDS)
                            .metadata(METADATA)
                            .build();

                    final UploadResult uploadResult;
                    uploadResult = upload.uploadFile(parameter);

                } catch (UploadException e1) {
                    e1.printStackTrace();
                } catch (IOException e1) {
                    e1.printStackTrace();
                }
            }
        });
```

Once the upload parameter is passed to the Upload API, it will in turn return an ```UploadResult``` object which has the NEM Hash. To get the NEM Hash, you can do:
```java
String nemHash = uploadResult.getNemHash();
```
We can use the NEM hash later for the Download.
Now we want our uploaded files to be displayed on the text area and populate our combo box. To do that, add in the following code:
```java

//will display file names on the text area
txtFiles.setText(uploadResult.getDataMessage().name());

//will populate the combox with uploaded files' names
cboFiles.addItem(uploadResult.getDataMessage().name());
```
#### What's Next?
Make your DOWNLOAD button functional in the next [guide](http://blog.proximax.io/coding-your-first-application-download/) 


"}]],"sections":[[10,0]]}

